Data Clinic 3: Text basics

1. Setting up

We will read the data from SQLite database into a R dataframe.

library(tm)
library(RSQLite)
library(dplyr)

####START LOADING THE DATASET#####
#Change the path of the dataset
db <- dbConnect(dbDriver("SQLite"), "/Volumes/SD/Downloads/database.sqlite")

tables <- dbGetQuery(db, "SELECT Name FROM sqlite_master WHERE type='table'")
colnames(tables) <- c("Name")

Emails <- data.frame(dbGetQuery(db,"SELECT * FROM Emails"))

emails_keep = Emails[,c(1:2,12:14,16,21)]
#This is the data frame you can start playing with

2. Analyzing Email Addresses

Analyzing the From/To email addresses

Now we are going to analyze the most common To/From email addresses.

First let’s start of with ExtractedTo column. We will plot the 15 most common receivers of messages.

cnt = count(emails_keep, ExtractedTo)
cnt_t = cnt[order( -cnt$n),]

cnt_t <- cnt_t[!(is.na(cnt_t$ExtractedTo) | cnt_t$ExtractedTo==""), ]

cnt_1 = cnt_t[1:15,]

library(ggplot2)
ggplot(cnt_1, aes(x=cnt_1$ExtractedTo, y=cnt_1$n)) +
  geom_bar(stat="identity", fill="#53cfff") +
  coord_flip() + 
  theme_light(base_size=16) +
  xlab("") +
  ylab("Number of Emails Sent To") + 
  theme(plot.title=element_text(size=14))

Now we are going find the top 15 senders of emails:

cnt = count(emails_keep, ExtractedFrom)
cnt_t <-cnt[order( - cnt$n),]
cnt_t <- cnt_t[!(is.na(cnt_t$ExtractedFrom) | cnt_t$ExtractedFrom==""), ]
cnt_1 = cnt_t[1:15,]

ggplot(cnt_1, aes(x=cnt_1$ExtractedFrom, y=cnt_1$n)) +
  geom_bar(stat="identity", fill="#53cfff") +
  coord_flip() + 
  theme_light(base_size=16) +
  xlab("") +
  ylab("Number of Emails Sent From") + 
  theme(plot.title=element_text(size=14))

We can observe there are quite a few duplicate senders/receivers in our plots who mainly differ in small textual representation eg. extra space in the email address.
We are going to clean that up now.
Using cosine distances we will analyze which are the most similar addresses.
For this we will concatenate the ExtractedTo and ExtractedFrom columns to get a larger amount of data to work with.
From there we will take only unique values.
Then using the stringdist package we can get Leventhstein (edit) distances between each two value.
We are going to filter this with a threshold.
Lastly we will some of the results whose edit distance are below that threshold.

require(stringdist)

df = unique(c(emails_keep$ExtractedTo ,emails_keep$ExtractedFrom))

string_distances = stringdistmatrix(df,df,method = "lv")

res = which((string_distances < 2) & (string_distances > 0) , arr.ind = TRUE)
print(length(res)/2)
## [1] 988
for(i in 1:nrow(res)) {
    if(i < length(res)/10){
      row <- res[i,]
      if(row[1] <= row[2]){
        cat(sprintf("Similar: %s and %s \n", df[row[1]], df[row[2]]))
      }
    }
}

6. Looking for mentions of a web address in the emails and calculating precision and recall (and ranked charts)

We are going to first extract websites that are mentioned in Hillary Clinton emails using a Regex.
Then we will count how many times each occurs website.
Lastly, we will compare our results with the perfect results.

res2 = regmatches(df1$paste.emails_keep.ExtractedSubject..emails_keep.ExtractedBodyText., regexpr("www\\..*?\\.(co.uk|com|org|gov|net)", df1$paste.emails_keep.ExtractedSubject..emails_keep.ExtractedBodyText.))

length(res2[nchar(res2) > 30])
## [1] 6
length(res2[nchar(res2) <= 30])
## [1] 81
res2 = res2[nchar(res2) <= 30]

df= do.call(rbind.data.frame, as.list(res2))
df = setNames(df,"websites")

cnt = count(df, websites)
cnt_t2 = cnt[order( -cnt$n),]
top_10_sites = cnt_t2[1:10,1]
print("Top 10 websites found with our model")
## [1] "Top 10 websites found with our model"
head(top_10_sites,10)
## # A tibble: 10 x 1
##    websites              
##    <fct>                 
##  1 www.thedailybeast.com 
##  2 www.ltstrategy.com    
##  3 www.huffingtonpost.com
##  4 www.salon.com         
##  5 www.ft.com            
##  6 www.guardian.co.uk    
##  7 www.myfoxdc.com       
##  8 www.newyorker.com     
##  9 www.nybooks.com       
## 10 www.nytimes.com
perfect_top_10_sites = c("www.guardian.co.uk", "www.thedailybeast.com", "www.nytimes.com", "www.newyorker.com", "www.washingtonpost.com","www.facebook.com",
"www.huffingtonpost.com","www.ft.com","www.messagelabs.com", "www.state.gov")
perf_top_10_sites= do.call(rbind.data.frame, as.list(perfect_top_10_sites))
perf_top_10_sites = setNames(perf_top_10_sites,"websites")

tp = nrow(intersect(top_10_sites,perf_top_10_sites))
fp = nrow(setdiff(top_10_sites,perf_top_10_sites))
fn = nrow(setdiff(perf_top_10_sites,top_10_sites))

precision = tp / (tp + fp)
recall = tp / (tp + fn)

sprintf("Precision %f", precision)
## [1] "Precision 0.600000"
sprintf("Recall %f", recall)
## [1] "Recall 0.600000"

We got a precision score of 0.6 and a recall score of 0.6.
These results aren’t really good but they aren’t that terrible.
Now we are going to do a precision-recall chart for ranked results.

x<-c()
y<-c()

cnt_t2 = cnt[order( -cnt$n),]
for (i in 0:20){
  top_i_sites = cnt_t2[1:i,1]
  tp = nrow(intersect(top_i_sites,perf_top_10_sites))
  fp = nrow(setdiff(top_i_sites,perf_top_10_sites))
  fn = nrow(setdiff(perf_top_10_sites,top_i_sites))

  precision = tp / (tp + fp)
  recall = tp / (tp + fn)

  x<-c(x,recall)
  y<-c(y,precision)
}

plot(unlist(x),unlist(y), ylab = "Precision", xlab = "Recall")

We notice that although the trend isn’t overly clear, higher precision rates occur with lower recall rates.
Similarly higher recall rates tend to reduce the precision.

4. Data cleaning

  1. We will first remove casing. For example we want “hillary” and “Hillary” to be the same term.
  2. We will then remove very short words. We only want words with 3 or more characters.
  3. We will then remove stop words. We pre-decided that words like “the” and “and” should be ignored.

We will also additionally:

  1. remove punctuation marks
  2. apply stemming
  3. remove excess whitespaces
require(tm)
library("SnowballC")
# basic cleaning
emails_keep$ExtractedBodyText <-  tolower(emails_keep$ExtractedBodyText)
emails_keep$ExtractedBodyText <- gsub('\\b\\w{1,3}\\b','',emails_keep$ExtractedBodyText)
emails_keep$ExtractedBodyText <- removeWords(emails_keep$ExtractedBodyText, stopwords("english"))
# additional stuff
emails_keep$ExtractedBodyText <- removePunctuation(emails_keep$ExtractedBodyText)
emails_keep$ExtractedBodyText <- stemDocument(emails_keep$ExtractedBodyText)
emails_keep$ExtractedBodyText <- stripWhitespace(emails_keep$ExtractedBodyText)

5. Per-sender TF-IDF and Vector Space Model

1. Identifying the different persons from the ExtractedFrom column

We can notice that the persons name is alawys at the start of the ExtractedFrom column and the email address follows afterwards starting with ‘<’ character.
Thus we are going to remove the email address part to focus only on the actual names.
Also we will remove the leading and trailing whitespaces.
Lastly we will visualize number of emails sent by each contact.

emails_keep$ExtractedFrom <- gsub('<.*','',emails_keep$ExtractedFrom)
emails_keep$ExtractedFrom <- gsub('^\\s+|\\s+$','',emails_keep$ExtractedFrom)

cnt = count(emails_keep, ExtractedFrom)
cnt_t <-cnt[order( - cnt$n),]
cnt_t <- cnt_t[!(is.na(cnt_t$ExtractedFrom) | cnt_t$ExtractedFrom==""), ]
cnt_1 = cnt_t[1:15,]

ggplot(cnt_1, aes(x=cnt_1$ExtractedFrom, y=cnt_1$n)) +
  geom_bar(stat="identity", fill="#53cfff") +
  coord_flip() + 
  theme_light(base_size=16) +
  xlab("") +
  ylab("Number of Emails Sent From") + 
  theme(plot.title=element_text(size=14))

We can see that this is a pretty good way to extract only the names of actual persons.

2. Concatenating all corresponding emails from each one of this person in one entry and cleaning the data

We will append all the emails a sender sent into a single entry.
We don’t have to clean the data any further as we already did that in step 4.

res = aggregate( ExtractedBodyText ~ ExtractedFrom, emails_keep, toString)
res_keep = res[ nchar(res$ExtractedBodyText) > 100, ]

3. Using cosine distance to find who are the persons that are most similar to Hillary

After our data was cleaned and aggregated, we will build a corpus.
From the corpus we will build a Term Document Matrix with TfIdf weighting and normalization.
Then we will use the slam library to calculate the cosine distances.
Lastly we will turn those distances into a dataframe and see whose emails are most similar to Hillary.

corp = Corpus(VectorSource(res_keep$ExtractedBodyText)) 

tdm = TermDocumentMatrix(corp, control = list(weighting = function(x) weightTfIdf(x, normalize = TRUE)))
colnames(tdm) = c(res_keep$ExtractedFrom)
library(slam)
cosine_dist_mat <- 1 - crossprod_simple_triplet_matrix(tdm)/(sqrt(col_sums(tdm^2) %*% t(col_sums(tdm^2))))

df_res = as.data.frame(as.table(cosine_dist_mat))

df_hillary = df_res[df_res$Docs.1 == 'H',]

df_hillary_sorted = df_hillary[ order( df_hillary$Freq), ]
colnames(df_hillary_sorted) = c("person","person2","cosine distance")
